1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,000
The Truman Show is one of my favourite movies.

2
00:00:02,000 --> 00:00:04,480
It's incredibly rare for a film to be as funny, cohesive,

3
00:00:04,480 --> 00:00:07,040
beautifully paced and rich in detail as The Truman Show.

4
00:00:07,040 --> 00:00:09,760
However, it's even rarer for a movie to go beyond this

5
00:00:09,760 --> 00:00:12,640
and give accurate, prophetic insights about the world.

6
00:00:12,640 --> 00:00:15,440
20 years later, and The Truman Show's allegorical message

7
00:00:15,440 --> 00:00:16,800
is more relevant than ever.

8
00:00:16,800 --> 00:00:18,800
But the only way we can truly understand its meaning

9
00:00:18,800 --> 00:00:20,240
is by diving into the story.

10
00:00:20,240 --> 00:00:22,400
The film begins with a monologue from Kristoff,

11
00:00:22,400 --> 00:00:24,320
who sets up the main premise of the movie.

12
00:00:24,320 --> 00:00:26,960
Truman is the unwitting star of a reality TV show

13
00:00:26,960 --> 00:00:28,160
centred around his life.

14
00:00:28,160 --> 00:00:30,960
Truman, a child abandoned at birth, has been brought up

15
00:00:30,960 --> 00:00:32,720
to believe that he is a normal guy living

16
00:00:32,720 --> 00:00:34,720
in the idyllic town of Seahaven Island.

17
00:00:34,720 --> 00:00:36,880
However, Truman's entire world is a lie.

18
00:00:36,880 --> 00:00:38,640
All the people he knows, including his mother,

19
00:00:38,640 --> 00:00:41,600
his best friend and his wife, are all paid actors.

20
00:00:41,600 --> 00:00:44,320
Seahaven Island is also fake, and is in reality

21
00:00:44,320 --> 00:00:46,560
just a huge setting close by a massive dome.

22
00:00:46,560 --> 00:00:48,800
This gives Kristoff, the director of The Truman Show,

23
00:00:48,800 --> 00:00:51,040
almost complete control over Truman's world.

24
00:00:51,040 --> 00:00:53,120
This ranges from the ability to control the weather

25
00:00:53,120 --> 00:00:55,680
to the day-night cycle and even the stars in the sky.

26
00:00:55,680 --> 00:00:58,080
Truman's every moment is broadcast around the world.

27
00:00:58,160 --> 00:01:01,120
With extra funding from the show coming from product placement.

28
00:01:01,120 --> 00:01:03,520
From the start of the film, we see a camera implanted

29
00:01:03,520 --> 00:01:05,760
in Truman's bathroom mirror, where Truman is pretending

30
00:01:05,760 --> 00:01:07,760
to be an explorer whilst getting ready for work.

31
00:01:07,760 --> 00:01:10,080
It's as though this is just another regular day for Truman,

32
00:01:10,080 --> 00:01:11,520
with him saying hello to his neighbors,

33
00:01:11,520 --> 00:01:13,360
making a coffee and getting into his car.

34
00:01:13,360 --> 00:01:15,040
But just as he's getting into his car,

35
00:01:15,040 --> 00:01:16,720
a stage slide drops from the sky,

36
00:01:16,720 --> 00:01:18,960
right onto the road outside of his house.

37
00:01:18,960 --> 00:01:20,640
Truman then walks over to inspect the light

38
00:01:20,640 --> 00:01:22,560
and sees that it says Sirius on it,

39
00:01:22,560 --> 00:01:24,480
referring to the brightest star in the night sky.

40
00:01:24,480 --> 00:01:26,080
But eerily, on his drive to work,

41
00:01:26,080 --> 00:01:28,640
the radio starts to run a story about a plane wreckage

42
00:01:28,640 --> 00:01:31,280
falling from the sky in order to explain the light.

43
00:01:31,280 --> 00:01:32,880
Here's a news flash just then,

44
00:01:32,880 --> 00:01:35,600
an aircraft in trouble began shitting parts

45
00:01:35,600 --> 00:01:37,760
as it flew over to see him in just a few moments ago.

46
00:01:37,760 --> 00:01:39,840
It then starts to talk about the dangers of flying,

47
00:01:39,840 --> 00:01:41,680
which is one of the first of many subtle ways

48
00:01:41,680 --> 00:01:43,360
that Krystal tries to influence Truman

49
00:01:43,360 --> 00:01:45,120
into staying on the island through fear.

50
00:01:45,120 --> 00:01:47,520
He is being subconsciously controlled by the radio.

51
00:01:47,520 --> 00:01:50,400
This subconscious manipulation then continues throughout the film.

52
00:01:50,400 --> 00:01:52,000
Like when Truman is asked by his boss

53
00:01:52,000 --> 00:01:54,160
to deal with something that will require a boat trip.

54
00:01:54,240 --> 00:01:56,960
By doing this, the boss is setting up Truman's aquaphobia

55
00:01:56,960 --> 00:01:59,280
as we see he is unable to even get in the boat,

56
00:01:59,280 --> 00:02:00,800
a phobia that's later revealed

57
00:02:00,800 --> 00:02:03,200
to be another subconscious manipulation of Truman.

58
00:02:03,200 --> 00:02:04,960
This whole day feels very strange for Truman,

59
00:02:04,960 --> 00:02:06,960
so he hurriedly comes back to his wife, Meryl,

60
00:02:06,960 --> 00:02:09,200
who then conspicuously shows off her new kitchen tool

61
00:02:09,200 --> 00:02:10,480
that she bought at the store,

62
00:02:10,480 --> 00:02:12,960
showing it off almost like she's advertising it.

63
00:02:12,960 --> 00:02:15,520
It's a dicer, greater, peeler, all in one.

64
00:02:15,520 --> 00:02:17,600
Never need sharpening, dishwasher safe.

65
00:02:17,600 --> 00:02:18,960
Truman becomes suspicious

66
00:02:18,960 --> 00:02:20,560
and when out with his best friend, Marlon,

67
00:02:20,560 --> 00:02:22,160
Truman's behavior starts to be off

68
00:02:22,160 --> 00:02:24,880
and he brings up his desire to leave and go to Fiji.

69
00:02:24,880 --> 00:02:27,120
Marlon catches that Truman is starting to wake up,

70
00:02:27,120 --> 00:02:28,720
so he quickly shoots down the idea.

71
00:02:28,720 --> 00:02:30,160
He doesn't want Truman escaping.

72
00:02:30,160 --> 00:02:31,520
That would break the whole game.

73
00:02:31,520 --> 00:02:32,960
In the next scene, we see Truman go off

74
00:02:32,960 --> 00:02:34,240
to spend some time on the beach,

75
00:02:34,240 --> 00:02:36,080
where he remembers the tragic boat accident

76
00:02:36,080 --> 00:02:38,880
that seemingly killed his father and gave him his aquaphobia.

77
00:02:38,880 --> 00:02:40,960
Kristoff then even hides in Truman's misery

78
00:02:40,960 --> 00:02:43,680
by adding a specific path of rain to follow Truman.

79
00:02:43,680 --> 00:02:45,440
And with Truman's breakdown growing,

80
00:02:45,440 --> 00:02:47,760
we see the audience's engrossed reactions.

81
00:02:47,760 --> 00:02:49,600
It's all these early scenes that serve to illustrate

82
00:02:49,600 --> 00:02:51,760
that the fictional Truman show can only function

83
00:02:51,760 --> 00:02:54,000
when Truman buys into this false reality.

84
00:02:54,000 --> 00:02:56,000
The Truman show therefore has to make sure

85
00:02:56,000 --> 00:02:57,920
that Truman can't escape his cage,

86
00:02:57,920 --> 00:02:59,600
or even see that he's in a cage

87
00:02:59,600 --> 00:03:02,640
if he knows that he's in a cage the whole game collapses.

88
00:03:02,640 --> 00:03:04,560
The ways that Kristoff keeps Truman deluded

89
00:03:04,560 --> 00:03:06,560
are the most striking aspects of the allegory.

90
00:03:06,560 --> 00:03:08,400
The most obvious and egregious of these

91
00:03:08,400 --> 00:03:10,240
is how Truman is kept complacent

92
00:03:10,240 --> 00:03:12,240
by exploiting his deepest fears.

93
00:03:12,240 --> 00:03:13,920
For example, Truman's aquaphobia

94
00:03:13,920 --> 00:03:16,160
works perfectly to keep Truman on the island.

95
00:03:16,160 --> 00:03:18,560
Kristoff even risks Truman overcoming this fear

96
00:03:18,560 --> 00:03:21,120
when he sends Truman to unsuccessfully board the boat.

97
00:03:21,120 --> 00:03:23,120
The fact that Truman can't overcome his phobia

98
00:03:23,120 --> 00:03:24,640
only reinforces this.

99
00:03:24,640 --> 00:03:27,200
Truman is also constantly barraged by propaganda

100
00:03:27,200 --> 00:03:29,680
and subliminal messages to induce a fear of flying.

101
00:03:29,680 --> 00:03:32,000
There are constant reminders of the dangers of flying.

102
00:03:32,000 --> 00:03:33,760
It takes this rampant fear mongering

103
00:03:33,760 --> 00:03:35,360
to keep Truman's delusion alive.

104
00:03:35,360 --> 00:03:37,680
However, this time the propaganda sluts to weaken.

105
00:03:37,680 --> 00:03:40,720
Truman still fantasizes about taking a flight to Fiji.

106
00:03:40,720 --> 00:03:42,080
His aquaphobia is still strong,

107
00:03:42,080 --> 00:03:43,680
but it's revealed that this is most likely

108
00:03:43,680 --> 00:03:45,600
because it originates from the undressed guilt

109
00:03:45,600 --> 00:03:46,960
over Truman's father's death.

110
00:03:46,960 --> 00:03:48,880
But it's not just the fear that influences Truman.

111
00:03:48,880 --> 00:03:50,720
The control that Kristoff has over his world

112
00:03:50,800 --> 00:03:51,440
is total.

113
00:03:51,440 --> 00:03:53,600
Everything Truman takes in on a daily basis

114
00:03:53,600 --> 00:03:55,360
is designed with a secret purpose.

115
00:03:55,360 --> 00:03:57,680
The TV he watches reinforces the message.

116
00:03:57,680 --> 00:03:59,040
The media always has headlines

117
00:03:59,040 --> 00:04:01,520
directly promoting whatever they want Truman to believe.

118
00:04:01,520 --> 00:04:03,040
Even the people that Truman talks to

119
00:04:03,040 --> 00:04:05,520
on a daily basis spout the same canned lines

120
00:04:05,520 --> 00:04:07,120
and positive affirmations.

121
00:04:07,120 --> 00:04:09,280
Propaganda is seeping into every aspect

122
00:04:09,280 --> 00:04:10,880
of Truman's life and society.

123
00:04:10,880 --> 00:04:12,160
You think I'm flying somewhere?

124
00:04:12,160 --> 00:04:13,520
Nope. Oh, good.

125
00:04:13,520 --> 00:04:15,840
A lot like its infiltration of our society.

126
00:04:15,840 --> 00:04:17,840
Just like Truman, we're always bombarded

127
00:04:17,840 --> 00:04:20,000
with propaganda just to keep us complacently

128
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:22,560
unaware of the delusions of modern ideology.

129
00:04:22,560 --> 00:04:24,480
Every day society tells us who we are,

130
00:04:24,480 --> 00:04:26,480
what we ought to do, and who our enemies are.

131
00:04:26,480 --> 00:04:28,400
Just like Truman, we're encouraged to ignore

132
00:04:28,400 --> 00:04:29,840
the clues that we're living in a lie,

133
00:04:29,840 --> 00:04:32,320
where we're made to still become wages in the matrix.

134
00:04:32,320 --> 00:04:34,800
And then everyone who buys into the societal delusion

135
00:04:34,800 --> 00:04:36,160
helps perpetuate it.

136
00:04:36,160 --> 00:04:38,560
This means that lots of well-meaning rational people

137
00:04:38,560 --> 00:04:41,520
are swept up to become mouthpieces of a failing system.

138
00:04:41,520 --> 00:04:44,000
The cracks are present in both reality and fiction.

139
00:04:44,000 --> 00:04:46,400
They just exist solely on the personal level for Truman

140
00:04:46,400 --> 00:04:48,800
rather than the societal level that we're starting to see.

141
00:04:48,800 --> 00:04:50,400
But what is the society-wide delusion?

142
00:04:50,400 --> 00:04:52,560
Well, in the Truman Show, it's obvious and literal.

143
00:04:52,560 --> 00:04:53,760
It's the premise of the movie.

144
00:04:53,760 --> 00:04:55,440
The Truman Show is a reality show.

145
00:04:55,440 --> 00:04:57,520
But how does this translate into our real world?

146
00:04:57,520 --> 00:04:58,960
Well, this is where it gets interesting.

147
00:04:58,960 --> 00:05:01,200
The Habitus is a tool used by sociologists

148
00:05:01,200 --> 00:05:04,240
for describing the ways in which a society's culture functions.

149
00:05:04,240 --> 00:05:06,320
Society rests upon an enormous amount

150
00:05:06,320 --> 00:05:08,400
of unsaid rules and expectations.

151
00:05:08,400 --> 00:05:10,240
These are often performed without thinking about them.

152
00:05:10,240 --> 00:05:12,640
It's more like a learned skill than a conscious decision.

153
00:05:12,640 --> 00:05:14,000
What would do the French intellectual

154
00:05:14,000 --> 00:05:15,360
who brought the term to prominence

155
00:05:15,360 --> 00:05:16,720
often compared it to sports?

156
00:05:16,720 --> 00:05:18,400
People tend to know the rules of the game.

157
00:05:18,400 --> 00:05:19,920
For example, it's generally accepted

158
00:05:19,920 --> 00:05:21,600
that when you're finished at the supermarket,

159
00:05:21,600 --> 00:05:22,960
you return your shopping cart.

160
00:05:22,960 --> 00:05:25,360
There's no personal reward or egotistic incentive.

161
00:05:25,360 --> 00:05:27,360
It's just a learned polite expectation.

162
00:05:27,360 --> 00:05:30,320
In the context of the supermarket, though, it's very important.

163
00:05:30,320 --> 00:05:32,320
The whole system would collapse without it.

164
00:05:32,320 --> 00:05:34,800
Some abstracts of the Habitus are nearly invisible

165
00:05:34,800 --> 00:05:36,720
because they seem so natural to us.

166
00:05:36,720 --> 00:05:39,840
Even your taste in musical food are influenced by the Habitus.

167
00:05:39,840 --> 00:05:41,760
This is because the cultural expectations

168
00:05:41,760 --> 00:05:44,000
that the Habitus instills go so deep.

169
00:05:44,000 --> 00:05:45,840
They're established from the moment you're born,

170
00:05:45,840 --> 00:05:47,920
reinforced throughout your childhood by your family

171
00:05:47,920 --> 00:05:50,720
and then further built upon by your education and work.

172
00:05:50,720 --> 00:05:53,760
This then makes the Habitus a self-perpetuating structure.

173
00:05:53,760 --> 00:05:55,520
Those brought up in certain Habitus

174
00:05:55,520 --> 00:05:57,600
will nurture its specific values in their children,

175
00:05:57,600 --> 00:06:00,240
for example, making sure the cycle continues.

176
00:06:00,240 --> 00:06:01,920
The Truman Show gives a literal picture

177
00:06:01,920 --> 00:06:03,440
of what a Habitus can look like.

178
00:06:03,440 --> 00:06:05,600
We can see all the actors in the fictional Truman Show

179
00:06:05,600 --> 00:06:06,880
is being sucked into this.

180
00:06:06,880 --> 00:06:08,800
The actors act in certain learned ways

181
00:06:08,800 --> 00:06:11,440
in order to perpetuate the essence of the Truman Show.

182
00:06:11,440 --> 00:06:13,920
Now, the key difference between fiction and reality

183
00:06:13,920 --> 00:06:14,960
is the incentive.

184
00:06:14,960 --> 00:06:17,040
Literally, the actors in the fictional Truman Show

185
00:06:17,040 --> 00:06:18,560
are being paid to play their parts.

186
00:06:18,560 --> 00:06:21,360
But in the real world, people play their parts in the Habitus

187
00:06:21,360 --> 00:06:24,400
because the Habitus itself has conditioned them into it.

188
00:06:24,400 --> 00:06:26,000
Everyone is one of the actors.

189
00:06:26,000 --> 00:06:27,520
Everyone makes the Delusion real.

190
00:06:27,520 --> 00:06:29,200
And what the Truman Show goes on to tell us

191
00:06:29,200 --> 00:06:31,120
is that when the Habitus has been altered

192
00:06:31,120 --> 00:06:33,840
into something too detached from an authentic society,

193
00:06:33,840 --> 00:06:36,480
cracks start to show when lies start to perpetuate,

194
00:06:36,480 --> 00:06:39,120
when the ego gets in the way, when power corrupts,

195
00:06:39,120 --> 00:06:40,640
the Habitus starts to break

196
00:06:40,640 --> 00:06:43,280
and this ripples throughout entire civilizations.

197
00:06:43,280 --> 00:06:44,720
See, throughout the movie's progression,

198
00:06:44,720 --> 00:06:47,200
we see Truman gradually wake up to the Delusion

199
00:06:47,200 --> 00:06:48,720
that has consumed his life,

200
00:06:48,720 --> 00:06:51,760
which inevitably causes a breakdown of the entire Habitus.

201
00:06:51,760 --> 00:06:53,600
The further Truman moves towards truth,

202
00:06:53,600 --> 00:06:55,520
the faster the Delusion collapses

203
00:06:55,520 --> 00:06:57,520
and thus the more resistance he faces.

204
00:06:57,520 --> 00:07:00,000
The Habitus of our world is just as deluded

205
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:01,360
as the one in the Truman Show.

206
00:07:01,360 --> 00:07:03,200
This is because what's valuable culturally

207
00:07:03,200 --> 00:07:06,480
has been drastically changed by reality TV and social media.

208
00:07:06,480 --> 00:07:08,000
The Truman Show almost predicted this

209
00:07:08,000 --> 00:07:09,920
with its commentary on reality TV.

210
00:07:09,920 --> 00:07:13,040
The vapid values of reality TV expanded to shape

211
00:07:13,040 --> 00:07:14,320
the entire Habitus.

212
00:07:14,320 --> 00:07:15,920
Now, limited to reality TV,

213
00:07:15,920 --> 00:07:17,440
and this doesn't seem too harmful,

214
00:07:17,440 --> 00:07:18,480
but it gets so much worse

215
00:07:18,480 --> 00:07:20,320
when you consider this in our own reality,

216
00:07:20,320 --> 00:07:23,440
especially with the effects of social media on our values.

217
00:07:23,440 --> 00:07:26,480
Nowadays, everyone's the star of their own reality TV show.

218
00:07:26,480 --> 00:07:28,880
People project vapid and unattainable standards

219
00:07:28,880 --> 00:07:31,040
by advertising a fake life on social media.

220
00:07:31,040 --> 00:07:33,440
That 14-year-old girls who use social media

